ADQUARTERS - Army senior leaders are reviewing the Army's operational plans after the service's top general earlier this month canceled a deployment of 4,000 soldiers to Europe before they ever made it across the Atlantic Ocean.Army leaders also have ordered that all major operations, both in the United States and abroad, be approved by the head of the Army's Joint Chiefs of Staff before they get green-lit.Army Chief of Staff Gen. Mark Milley confirmed in a hearing on Monday that the decision to block the "Europe 8" planning effort stemmed from the service's efforts to prepare for the possibility of an imminent war in Europe and the related need to protect the nation's homeland.The Joint Chiefs of Staff "recommended to the president and the National Security Council, in conjunction with the department, that the Department of Defense would not be prepared to fight on more than one front in the next year," Milley said in response to a question from Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont. "And there's only one front that is that exists right now."Milley didn't elaborate on what that front is beyond the obvious mention of Russia's invasion of Ukraine."We are not the most ready Department of Defense that we've ever been, and it's because of the number of fights that we are fighting concurrently at this time," Milley added. "And so, what we're trying to do is reduce the amount of fights we're in, and therefore we will be more ready."The order to block the deployment has angered both Poland and Romania, which had requested U.S. support as they prepare to defend against potential Russian aggression."There is now an important question about military solidarity between NATO allies," Polish Permanent Representative to NATO Tadeusz Iwinski said, according to the Reuters news agency. "Does NATO mean something or not?"Poland had called for "immediate activation" of a NATO defense plan if Russian forces move into the former Soviet satellite countries, with Romania also saying it needed to bolster military ties with the United States."NATO is a security guarantee for us," said Romanian Defense Minister Nicolae Ciuca. "I want to have it, and I can guarantee that Romania will be there to defend [NATO's] territory and NATO allies."Milley's comment to Leahy on Monday could refer to a series of ongoing conflicts in which the United States finds itself, including in Russia's war in Ukraine, which has seen Russia targeted with stiff sanctions, as well as a series of attacks on the U.S. homeland, including cyberattacks, by the People's Republic of China.It is those cyberattacks that Milley referred to when he said that the Pentagon is trying to reduce the number of conflicts it finds itself in.The chief of staff pointed to the Defense Digital Service, a joint effort of service and defense-wide information technology personnel, as working to reduce the number of security vulnerabilities the Pentagon finds itself in."We are reducing the number of security vulnerabilities that are in the DOD system," Milley said Monday.We're also looking at securing the homeland."We're not gonna fight on two fronts at the same time," he added. "We can't manage both at the same time, all those kinds of things. So it is a delicate balance at this point of time."Milley's comments come in the same week that the Pentagon announced the cancellation of eight major training exercises in Europe, North America and South Korea that had been scheduled for this month.The cancellations were in line with the administration's broader strategy aimed at bolstering the alliance with South Korea.They come under the same National Defense Strategy that Milley noted in his testimony.That strategy outlines the top priorities and threats facing the United States, as well as how the military will be used to counter those threats, including through operations against both state and non-state actors.It was under this strategy that Milley noted the need to reduce the conflicts currently in place, but how much of a role does the Joint Chiefs of Staff play in determining what operations are pursued, given the president's control of the use of the armed forces under the Constitution?It appears not much, according to a new Defense Department directive that provides guidance to the military services "for ensuring the department's military actions comply with law."In the directive, signed by Deputy Defense Secretary Kathleen Hicks and released on Monday, the Pentagon says that "the president retains the sole and exclusive authority to authorize" the use of military force and determines the appropriate roles and missions for the armed forces.This means that Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Milley will play the role of advisor on what operations should be pursued.Still, the role of that advice is significant, especially given the comments of Milley this week to Sen. Leahy and the comments made by former Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Martin Dempsey in a 2014 testimony before the National Commission on the Structure of the Air Force."It's not just the capability of your force," Dempsey told members of the commission. "It's the will of your country behind you."During his Senate testimony, Milley, likewise a former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman, said, "the president makes the decision. But the senior military officials provide him the options in the context of the law, and the law has to be considered."
Ransomware operators are moving to cloud services to escape detection
By CSO Online staff Cyber resiliency
New research by Emsisoft has found that ransomware groups are increasingly moving to cloud storage services to evade detection by law enforcement, security analysts, researchers and cybercriminals.
The findings were part of the company's first Trend Analysis of Ransomware in 2022, which examines common behaviours and tactics cybercriminals use to deploy and operate ransomware.
Since Emsisoft's research found that more than 95% of ransomware groups make use of cloud storage, the company decided to analyse the ways in which these criminals leverage cloud platforms.
Cloud services have become the main "hideouts" for ransomware operations. Using the cloud, hackers can quickly evade detection as each cloud provider has its own infrastructure and the threat actors change their methods each time.
The researchers found that the majority of ransomware actors use Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud and Amazon Web Services (AWS) cloud platforms. Ransomware operators were especially drawn to the ability to create and terminate multiple virtual machines that provided easy access to cloud virtual machine instances, the ability to quickly scale for large operations, cloud service integration tools and cloud management interfaces.
More insights into the report and the ransomware attack findings can be found in a video presentation by Malware Research Specialist Peter Kruse on the Emsisoft blog. Key takeaways include:
Cloud hosting makes hacking easier – the cloud offers the option to create and remove virtual machines without any restrictions and at any time. The cloud also offers the ability to scale up a wide operation to host a range of infrastructure, such as domain registrations, email senders, or infrastructure for website traffic.
The cloud providers fight back – cloud service providers understand the risks involved in hosting ransomware attacks, and have begun to fight back. Microsoft recently announced an initiative to "cut costs for cybersecurity" for all Azure customers, including free protection against threats. Meanwhile, Google Cloud also announced the addition of new security protection features. Amazon seems to be the latest to join the club, announcing a plan to add enhanced security for AWS customers.
Attackers favour popular solutions like Azure, Azure VMs or Google, Google Cloud – the two most popular cloud providers as per statistics provided by Netcraft are Azure and Google. Microsoft Azure, in particular, is a popular option for ransomware attackers due to its rich feature set and popularity.
Attackers can easily use cloud services - ransomware hackers can easily use cloud providers directly without setting up dedicated services. AWS has gained great popularity among these actors due to its free services. Many ransomware operators don't even make use of dedicated domain registrations and mail service providers to distribute or deliver their cryptors' decrypt files because it's too much trouble to maintain, and Amazon Simple Email Service (SES) is free and very popular.
Ransomware groups exploit vulnerabilities across the enterprise – the Emsisoft report highlighted how hackers are no longer targeting specific types of companies. Instead of targeting only large organisations, they now opt for any system they can leverage as a launch point to launch a broader campaign.
Ransomware groups increasingly target small industries – due to their use of vulnerabilities, there has been a major shift in the ransomware landscape, with small and medium businesses as the main focus of most recent attacks.
"Microsoft, Google, and Amazon are aware of the risks posed by ransomware actors, and have begun to fight back. But it's up to each one of us to do our part! It's important that everyone is proactive in securing their environment against the rising threat of ransomware," concluded the firm.
In addition to the cloud services analysis, the report also shared insights into how the ransomware groups behind the recent attacks are utilising Tor and the use of VPNs/proxies.
More than 50 per cent of ransomware operations run on a Tor network, with the anonymity provided by the network proving to be a useful tool that keeps security analysts from tracking where the threat actors are coming from.
According to the report, Tor's high bandwidth limits and the use of Tor exit nodes make it difficult for cybersecurity professionals to identify if Tor is being used to access a compromised network. Therefore, threat actors now frequently use the Tor network, which makes the attacks more anonymous and undecipherable. However, Tor users have also discovered that in many cases, the Tor network is not actually the most effective anonymiser one can get their hands on.
"While Tor is a popular anonymisation tool, the reality is that its effectiveness could be further compromised once an attacker has a handle on a system," said Emsisoft.
In the second section of the report, Emsisoft found that a number of ransomware groups often utilise virtual private networks (VPNs) and proxies to make it more challenging for others to track them. However, there is a large difference between the actual usage of VPNs and proxies and how popular they truly are.
"With some VPN providers available free of charge, as well as the wide array of options available for proxy servers, it is no surprise that these are popular alternatives to get around tracking mechanisms for ransomware operators," said the company. "Our research shows that 40 per cent of actors use VPNs."
Many of these actors typically use free VPN or privacy services, but many don't use a VPN – and even without the use of a VPN or proxy service, an attacker can often easily disguise malicious tools and activities on the target PC with a single download.
Attackers utilise a variety of IP addresses and countries – attackers typically avoid overuse of a particular IP address or even a provider, as this could allow for attribution to an attacker.
The Emsisoft report recommended that users should not open emails or click on suspicious links, and organisations should patch their systems immediately. Users should also keep vigilant with their firewalls, create a robust defence, including email filters, and should regularly back up data.
The Emsisoft Trend Analysis of Ransomware is published quarterly and provides expert insights into emerging trends, research findings, and important ransomware developments. The first report is also available for download here.

instruction: Do we have a moral obligation to explore space, or should we focus on solving Earth's problems first?
prompt: r longHOME approximately pressure Gill HE
combined_input: Do we have a moral obligation to explore space, or should we focus on solving Earth's problems first? r longHOME approximately pressure Gill HE
generated_output:
LEN PETERSON and JIM GERAGHTY have joined us to discuss the U.S. space policy and how it's a good time to re-nationalize the program as well. I think this is a very interesting conversation. We' re very pleased to have you here. JIM GERAGHTY, NATIONAL REVIEW: Thank you. You're welcome. You talk about the U.S. space program. Is there an International space program? There is an international space station that's been in the works since the 1990s, really to show the benefits of cooperation and how you can get different countries together. What's the status of that? That program is going on as we speak, and we're actually looking into launching another one to get the private sector involved that's called Orion and will make trips around the moon, etc. This is a new era. No more Russians. Americans are driving their own program. It's been stalled in Congress, but I hope they vote on it tonight. Do we have a moral obligation to extend humanity's presence to other places in the universe? GEN. BURGESS: I think as humans on this planet, we're going to continue to explore and try to understand our universe. It may sound strange coming from a man who has spent virtually his entire adult life in uniform, but this is a very important part of making us better as a civilization, I believe. We're going to continue to explore. It used to be exploration was the military's domain. Now it's just not done anymore. So now we have science to help us. I think it's incumbent upon us as a civilization to not only explore, to know more about the world in which we live, to have a better picture, if you will. But also in the process of doing this, it creates a tremendous economic engine. If we look at what's happening in India, for example, they actually have made what they call Indian Space and Space Medicine a mandate in India. That means they're now going to go into higher levels of education in their universities and in their medical programs. So we can use space to not only educate, but also to grow economically and technologically. So it's a twofer. You have those good uses with space. PETERSON: And there are other countries that are interested not only in the knowledge factor, what we learn from space programs, but also from the technological advances. So whether it's the shuttle that the U.S. has, there's China, there's India, there's Russia that are able to make use, for example, from the technology from that. GERAGHTY: Yes. So this international cooperation with space is actually growing. And it's not just that everybody is doing their own thing. And this whole international space station thing has been a fairly costly project. In the 1990s, the U.S. was supposed to pay 123 million. It turned out to be well over a billion, and even that might be a bit of an understatement. But, you know, look at the technology that came out of that. And this is the whole point of this. For all the good that NASA is doing itself in terms of research and technology, it is doing much more interesting stuff in conjunction with other countries. And the question is, will it always be just a collaboration? Will we see nations like India, China, et cetera, just taking over, and in effect, taking our place? You know, we had a good run. Let's get some of our citizens jobs back. Some of our technology. Or will we be better off with the U.S. leading? That's a policy issue. I think you're going to have to get your Congressman engaged if you want to see this happening. HELEN PETERSON, WALMART VP: I think it's going to happen. I think it will grow. It's been a great place for growth. We do a lot of our research on earth, as you know. We're thinking of ways to make research accessible for a broad variety of people. And I think space's going to be an amazing place for that. JIM GERAGHTY, NATIONAL REVIEW: So far we've taken it for granted that countries in Europe and beyond would cooperate with us on space programs because we're, in some respects, a global super power for the space program. What changed? PETERSON: I think you're going to have to take a broader view of what space is. You talked about the space station and what space is. But as the worlds become smaller, more connected, communication become more difficult because it has to be more secure because it becomes more important, that's where space will come in, and that is already happening. GERAGHTY: Can we talk about that for a second? What are the problems that we're solving on earth today that are connected to space? Or is this simply just cool rocket ships going to the moon, which is fine, but that's sort of my view of space, is that we are just going on this adventure that we could have gone to at any time during the last 40 or 60 years, and now a lot of us are actually interested in where this is going. PETERSON: So I think I would look at what's been happening recently. If we look at where, 10 years ago, where we were, we were looking with a view. We had a window on where things were, but not a real, 3D view of what's happening. We didn't know what was happening to our planet, that we couldn't see all the things happening around us. So now we can actually look and see those environmental problems that we have. So I would say that the advancer technology in space is helping us solve problems on the planet. We take water from the bottom of the ocean and put it in the ground to help a drought area. We provide a 3-D view of the earth like never before. When there is an earthquake, we can look at the location right to the microsecond. So you actually are able to see that things are moving faster than you ever have before. So it really, to me, is an exploration tool that's helping us solve problems on our planet, just as it once was. GILL: And to follow that up, could you talk about one or two specific advances that in your mind have made that connection. Specifically, satellites like, you know, GPS or something else? PETERSON: So we talked about how we connect in this world. It's all about connectivity. So satellites have become a very important part of communication. They're also very important in looking at the earth. But a lot of people don't know that our satellites are also helping us understand our planet. For example, we look at weather. We actually have satellites that are orbiting the earth from space. And that's not only to look and see, of course, where the tornadoes are, where the hurricanes are, but also on the bottom of the sea, because we are able to sense the bottom of the ocean. With the earthquakes and tsunamis, that was a phenomenal advancement that was made to be able to look at those events as they're happening. So now the information that we get from the satellites is able to help us with the things we care about. GERAGHTY: I think the U.S. will still be involved in space long after the shuttles fly their last flights and the space station falls into the sea. But will we -- if we see, as this conversation suggests, that these are very useful things on earth, will Americans be better off if China and India take our place, or will U.S. lead in space? And more money and innovation and research going on there, it's just going to end up benefiting us down the line. PETERSON: I think when you look at the advancements -- and you don't have to call them Chinese to get these technologies and that there are a lot of technology that's coming from China because they can produce. But they're also creating a lot of things because they can use their own technology and are using it on the earth. GERAGHTY: So I guess my question is whether there is a threat to those who believe in free markets, that as this cooperation goes on, more of the benefits of the cooperation flow and just the research itself. PETERSON: I think what you've got to look at in the technologies that I mentioned earlier are being used to help other nations. You look at water use. You know how to use a technology to use water on their planet when their crops have drought. They're working on that. The communication technology has helped them advance with their economy and with their businesses. GERRAGHTY: Are there national security implications as well? I mean you do get a lot of information and a lot of things on the earth. GERAGHTY: What information could you get at our expense? PETERSON: So the information that I would look at very closely now, as I've worked in this area, is where the satellite is. It's no longer a foreign policy when it's in the U.S. or U.S.-based, or U.S.-produced. They actually use it in other countries to help bring to their country what they want to use it for. It doesn't matter where the satellite is. But where it's placed makes a big difference. And we're seeing that now. Because as we move more and more on the internet and things like that, it's an advancement that's happening. But there are nations that have a view that if they can put what's called a ground station in the country, that they have the control of that data and how that data is going to be used. So you have to look and not just at the satellites, but whether it's actually in control on the ground by a sovereign nation or sovereign people in a sovereign country. GERRAGHTY: Are some nations, China? PETERSON: Yes. So China, of course, would be right up there. But I would have to say that in many ways, these nations are using that technology to help others and make an advantage to help their own nation. GILL: Let's talk about the actual launch and what we can expect from Congress tonight. I mean, we're seeing that we now have a very interesting political atmosphere in Congress, which is going to complicate negotiations. If in fact the Democrats and the Republicans in Congress end up with 51 seats in their respective parties, would that create a roadblock in terms of approval of this funding? GERAGHTY: I am hoping that it does, yes. I think as Jim has pointed out, the shuttles are getting to the end of their lives. The International Space Station is worthwhile. We also need a vehicle to get astronauts and supplies into low earth orbit, where we have been for 20 years or so. This decision in the next couple days. And this isn't a big deal as far as the budget goes. You're talking about a few billion dollars a year. And that's a lot of money, but it's a trivial amount in the context of the big government that we have. We will probably end up funding something. It could delay the Orion program. We might have to send a smaller number of astronauts to space just to get it done. But, it's going to happen. It's going to happen this week. They're going to get something. I think that Republicans, particularly, should say, look, I think they're doing the right thing, by the way. I think NASA itself should work on the space program as a separate program from the rest of government. GILL: I think the problem right now is a lot of money is going to just be handed out to the states. We're going to get a lot more on the transportation infrastructure, which we will talk about right after, I'm sure. That's an issue that I want to talk about too. Right now, we want to talk about space. Should we have a national policy, not based on what other countries are doing, and say, okay, we're going to get this done within a certain amount of time? Or do you think the country can live without that? GERAGHTY: I actually just wrote a piece on the Hill yesterday about why this, in fact, is important. I mentioned how I used to be a Space Camp kid. A lot of my friends from grade school actually went to Space Camp. And we had this idea that in the 1970s, there would be these huge space stations with Americans and Russians living there and doing incredible things. And then the reality was, things turned out differently. We sort of lost the plot a little bit. Even though we were still getting more out of it, but not as much because we were putting so much more into the other parts of the federal government. And we lost the vision, which we're now getting back in some ways, with what NASA's doing with the private sector. And, you know, I'm not a huge fan of Obama here. But that does sound cool. I do want to go to space. I do want to know more about how it affects us on the planet. So I could work with the idea of putting more money towards NASA. And that would be in line with my libertarian streak. PETERSON: I actually, you know, this is in the middle of the night here in Virginia. And I have to admit, as I watch, it's almost a dream come true. When you talk about going into space and being able to see the different things that are done in the space station that the private sector's going to bring to that and the technology that will be coming, it makes it more exciting. And in many ways, if we lose all this, we will lose our place. This is an opportunity for us to show our future generations how great and innovative we can be. GILL: I'm in full agreement with all of that. And the reason why I asked the question is because some members of Congress are saying, hey, you know what, you can't spend any money unless states are also able to get it from the federal government for infrastructure projects. So the reality is, we are losing sight of the bigger federal national interest and what we should be doing nationally. We're now putting more money in the state and how much money the state is giving you. GERAGHTY: Oh, there are still federal programs. You can get an R & D grant, for example, and that's supposed to go to the states. PETERSON: I think they can get there together. And I think the question is, are we going to be able to fund the things that are important across the United States or not? generated_output:
ADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra Gill HEADlongHOME pipelineextra
The experiment above shows how the force of gravity is a vertical pull that causes the apple to fall (and crash) to the ground. What about the feather? There is no action, no force, behind the feather either, right? You and I know that the apple and the feather fell, but it is hard to perceive why since there was no force acting on either of the objects. Yet, there were!
According to Einstein, “When you have to put on a new shirt but don’t have a chance until later: that’s gravitation.” Einstein’s genius is that he took the everyday concept of gravity (those rocks) and changed the frame of reference. By changing the frame (and doing very careful mathematics), “When you have to put on a new shirt but don’t have a chance until later: That’s inertia” or “non-actionable force” became a reality. He proved that gravity and even the laws of motion hold within a frame of reference as long as you make the right corrections.
What do non-actionable forces have to do with you as a leader? Quite a bit, I think.
So What Are Non-Actionable Forces?
When you are a leader, you are surrounded by non-actionable forces, and it’s impossible to make them a reality. As with gravity, there are lots of causes and reasons for these forces, yet you alone cannot control them. They include:
Your team’s culture: In our 30-years of experience on the corporate executive team, the single factor that prevented us from being better leaders was not a lack of education or experience. Rather, it was our lack of understanding how deeply rooted our team’s organizational culture ran. Leaders come and leaders go, but culture lives on (and is often worse when new executives arrive!).
Time: For your team, for yourself, for your vendors, for your customers, for your shareholders, etc.
Economic factors: GDP, interest rates, government regulations.
Psychological factors: Emotions, personality, moods, stress, motivation, etc….
What does all this mean….
First, the answer to “Why is everything that leaders do difficult” is, “Because everything is difficult as a leader.”
Second, the good news. To create lasting results, we must start with what we do have control over, including:
Our commitment to serve – we can decide that our goal is to serve and build trust; and once we believe that the only path to reach that goal is to build trust, we will begin to understand the importance of listening and asking as much as telling. (Remember that if you are in a leadership position, your role is to serve. You have little control for what is outside your world.)
Our values – we can be confident that our organizational culture has values built-in, but it could be the worst case in the world, and we cannot choose it if we intend to be better leaders.
Our skills – we can continue honing the skills we know will help us. For example, a well-developed “growth mindset” will help us embrace changes to our skills more quickly.
Our relationships – we can continue to work with people as the best teams work. In the best teams, all members look for the best in each other and strive never become jaded.
Honestly, the list of things we don’t have control over is longer, but that does not mean we have to give in to them. We’d all like to be a little taller, but for sure a lot of other things are in our control, and what we do has a direct impact on lasting results.
We hope that you will join us as we examine non-actionable forces in greater depth in future posts. We’d also like to hear from you.
Let us know some of situations or choices of where you struggled for control and that, in the back of your mind, you knew there was actually nothing to control! Or let us know some of the success you’ve had by working on those things that are not truly actionable.

W GATS HIS PHONE ON, a woman's voice said, "Gill? Is that you?" "Yes," he said. "I'm here." "I'd heard you moved back," she said, "but I thought it was just another of your jokes. Is it all true? Are you really back?" "I'm back," he said. r'm on the road. I'll be back down to the office tomor-
278 THE HIGH CRUSADE morning. I told you, Tina...it was a big change of pace. I mean, what I was doing—in the lab, right? I don't miss it at all- "What are you doing now, Gill?" she said. "Are you a consultant or something?" "Sort of." "Sort of?" she said. "Yes, I guess that's the best way of describing it." "Is there anything I can do for you?" she said. "Maybe. You must know about the new computer system at the bank." "I know about it." "Well. They're having problems with it." "Troubleshooting is best done on-site, I guess." "Yes," she said, "you're probably right. I'd rather talk to you than to anyone else in the company." "Well," he said, thinking about it, "why don't you take some time off and come meet me. I'm checking out some new places. Maybe we can go to dinner." "I don't think I can," she said. "No, you can't. The problem is, Tina, I was going to go see my mother and sisters. I only get to see them once a year. If I don't go now, I probably wouldn't get to make the trip, and things have changed so much." "You know, Gill," she said, "every time I read the papers, it looks like another of your outrageous ideas is in the works. It makes it hard for me to believe you." "It's true," he said. He told her about some of the plans he had. It made him uneasy to talk about them. At that time he wasn't entirely sure how they would do, whether they were realistic or not.
279 REVELATIONS Gill still knew Tina hadn't forgiven him for leaving New York, and she was probably right. He'd made a mess of things for a while and he'd been out of touch with people long enough that some of them probably thought he was dead. By the time she'd talked to him, most of them figured he'd been killed in a traffic accident. Her attitude was still cool, but it wasn't quite unfriendly, either. He'd made her laugh with his stories, and he enjoyed the way she laughed. And she knew him well enough so they had nothing to hide from each other. It was nice to be around her again. "You must be very excited," she said. "It could be big, Tina. This is a big idea." "That's part of what gives me the idea," he said, pacing the floor, "when I stop to think about it. As a project, it's huge. The kind of money that's going to go into this is amazing." "Well, we already live in unbelievable luxury." "Yeah, but not on this earth. We're not the real thing either." "Where is 'the real thing,' Gill?" he said. "I don't know that, not on this level, I guess. Maybe people are going to go out and get rich and that's going to be a real luxury. But then what? This isn't real life to me."
280 THE HIGH CRUSADE "You mean, on a primitive world people are going to have to work for what they get and that's going to be a big luxury? Why don't they just get the big luxury on earth right now? Don't they have anything to learn?" "Probably not. That's what I mean." "Well, I don't get it." "I think I do," she said. She was still standing where she had been, only more alertly than before. "It is going to be a luxury," she said, "for people to do things for themselves. Even things we could do in a second or a minute or a second or a minute...things they could grow themselves without any help, like food or homes or clothes...even if we had those things, it would be a luxury to do things for them- selves, don't you think it would? I guess that's what's behind this whole thing." "I don't know," he said. "Maybe. All I know is, a lot of people are going to get rich and they're going to have to figure out what they're going to do with that money. They can't just sit around doing nothing. They're going to have to pick something, and some of them are going to build new worlds." He thought of all those great works of science-fiction in which the universe was colonized, one planet at a time, a man's vision of the future. He was beginning to believe that they had been right, that the future really would be like this. He'd always suspected the human race would grow into the universe
281 REVELATIONS and populate the universe with its own works, the human species spread over the heavens with all of its arts and its science and its knowledge. It hadn't been a bad idea for fiction, but he had to admit now that it was likely to be better than that. As he thought about it, though, the idea seemed a little less than marvelous. It seemed like a lot of work for all those wonderful things. He began to wonder why they'd started doing everything themselves at all. He'd known about the planets and the constellations of stars for a while, but he'd forgotten what an achievement that had been. r t's interesting," Gill said. "I wouldn't have believed it. Not until just a few years ago. But it's been happening since we were first able to see out there, and from now on it will only keep going. I don't know what the end game will be. I guess we'll find out." "Well," she said, "I guess you're going to stay down there forever. I know what you can't bear. You've got to come and see us again."

1 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO by James Sallis PALOMA DE LA PAZ was one of those towns you might imagine to be the creation of an imaginative personality — perhaps a novelist or painter. Its whitewashed colonial buildings, dating from the Spanish rule of the region, were spread out along a canyon road that hugged the base of an escarpment, the houses seeming to be tumbling down toward a river gorge below. The main street formed a sort of arc, or amphitheater, with the mountains at one side and at the other the river itself, but the homes looked more like a collection of residences attached to one another as well as the walls of the town. The houses were simple but well built, and, with some effort (and money), they would be suitable as anything from a simple vacation home to something rather fancy. At the center of the village was a square, the site of one of two large town buildings built of adobe and shaped in an unusual fashion like the capitals of the ancient Greek columns. One faced the main street, which it dominated, while the other stood along the river, a more subdued presence. The buildings were in part open to each other, their roofs flowing together but for a low wall of the adobe at the edge of each. In this area there was a large open fireplace built into the side walls,
2 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO which was always kept alight in the dead of winter. Around the fire pit, in a stone basin, were three massive fountains topped by bronze statues: a man and a woman of different designs, and a third statue of a man in Spanish armor. There were no trees in the village. Not only were the trees of that country not adapted for that kind of climate, but the trees tended to be used for building and to help stave off erosion. When the trees were cut, the branches were often shaped into intricate designs that were placed over the buildings. On the outside of these simple and yet exquisite structures were the homes of the villagers. In one, a boy sat in his room with his schoolbooks in the semidarkness. He worked with his pencil, scratching his name on a drawing on a blackened white stone, with his own name underneath the words, OHIO STATE UNIVERSITY. Above the names was a large red star—the logo of the university—that somehow stood out in the dim light. He was nine years old, but as a result of a local tragedy he had been left to grow up with the responsibilities of a man. He had no name on his papers, no family, not even a way to get home. He just had schoolwork, and the drawings in his notebook. He never talked to anyone about them—even to his teacher, with whom he had a good relationship with. When he was finished with his work, he set his books on a windowsill and lay down on his bed in the room, which in the darkness looked larger by far than it did in the daylight. Near midnight the door to the boy’s room opened, and a man walked in. It wasn’t one of the men generally present in the house. Even a child could tell the difference in their walk and their look. The man went to the boy’s bed, knelt beside him, touched his hair. “Rodolfo, my son? Are you feeling well tonight?” The boy sat up, looked at his adoptive
3 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO father. This was a nightly event. The man put his arm around Rodolfo, and the two men then lay down on the bed. And slept, Rodolfo between the two men—as always.
4 A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO A few days later, Rodolfo sat in the town square with the teachers of the community and several dozen students. The old woman who had raised Rodolfo taught elementary school, and this was the first time Rodolfo had taken classes in higher mathematics. His teacher was the boy’s father—a man Rodolfo had never seen until a few months back. Tonight the room was completely dark except for a gas or electric taper used for special occasions. The boy was in the last row on the right, on top of one of the stone tables in the square. It was at some distance from the other tables. Rodolfo’s teacher sat at one of the tables, between two other teachers, and the boy’s adoptive parents sat near the man. Rodolfo had been through the lesson twice—once with the students and a second time alone with the teacher. Now the teacher had left the meeting room and was returning, bringing drinks for the men and women. The boy waited until the man had taken a seat before asking his question. “So, Rodolfo has all the right, but if he’ s in the back row, he has nothing. Is that what you mean? Is that how it goes? I don’t get it.” “Come, now, my son, I have only told you that I gave you power over the other. Come now, be kind enough to admit you understand. Let me tell you of another. Do you remember the days you worked all together in the fields, when we plowed? I remember.
5 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO You see the plowing horse as well as I? She was a great horse. Her name was Elena, and she was beautiful.” “Yes, my father. I do remember.” “Good,” said the man. He pulled a brass goblet off the table. “This, Rodolfo, is the power I give you, the gift I give you. This is the brilliance you have, to which you must always hold.” “Yes, sir,” said Rodolfo. “Now I give you this, the second power,” said the man. He brought out another pitcher, and it was filled with golden beer. The man went around and handed each of the men in the audience a goblet filled with the fine beer, and he and the other teachers took one. One of the women refused, as did Rodolfo. “I have something to show you,” said the teacher. He stood and went to Rodolfo and took the notebook from his lap. “This you have made yourself.” “Yes. I made it myself.” “So you are a man.” The teacher returned to his seat, took up his own beer and drank. He sat beside Rodolfo and took the manuscript from the boy. He smiled to himself, thinking of what was inside. No one in the meeting was interested in anything beyond the book. The boy was the son of the leader, the heir to the family. He had come by power and influence as well as by brilliance, and everyone understood that he was one of the special children. “Let me see,” said the man beside him, reading.
6 A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO The room began to hum with talk and laughter. A woman reached over and squeezed Rodolfo’s hand, while her eyes glanced lovingly at his father. The other students in the audience took their own goblets and sipped their beer. Rodolfo himself was unperturbed. While he’d grown up a pampered orphan, he’d had few friends and never a girlfriend. He’d always been able to read about the lives of men who were far, far superior—in some cases far beyond what he’d ever be himself. That was the difference from the beginning. He had to be a leader, and what a poor choice of occupations for that was he couldn’t have imagined. So he’d done what the man had taught him, learned the mathematics, learned the way to read and write. He’d learned the ways of leadership in a manner that was nearly as rigorous—to be sure, it involved less suffering—but no less rigorous than the life of a soldier, a policeman, an accountant. These men knew that life was hard, that things were far from fair. And Rodolfo understood that he bore enormous responsibility, though it might as yet seem he didn’t quite understand what that was himself. “The gift, the power, of Elena,” the man said, pausing the reading to look up at Rodolfo. “You have it yourself. It will serve you in ways I cannot see.” “Yes, sir,” said Rodolfo, nodding. “The book I made, it is nothing.” His teacher laughed at that. “Yes, it is nothing—if you read like you write. No. This is a great gift.” He smiled again at the boy’s work.
7 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO “You know, Rodolfo, that the gift of Elena is what keeps us all here. It is what kept us
8 A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO from leaving. We will all come here, when it is time. We will come to the door and we will step through; we will come and see what the angels and the demons of the mountain have to offer.” The teachers laughed and clapped Rodolfo on the back, while from the tables came an occasional shifting of the bottle glasses. “I don’t want to miss it,” said Rodolfo. He raised his goblet to be filled—the same beer as his father, now filled with gold- colored liquid. The other men rose and went to the door that led to the meeting-room kitchen. Rodolfo followed the teachers and remained at the door while they emptied their goblets and the others. The door closed, and the boy was now alone in the room. The voices of his parents and teacher filled the air, telling stories with all their drinks, and with the laughter of the other teachers. Rodolfo listened but he did not fully hear these things they spoke, though some of it reached his mind. Perhaps that is what kept him awake that night—for a time, at least. It must have been close to two in the morning when he finally fell asleep, and while he was asleep he was troubled by the things he’d seen and heard, by things he remembered.
9 CHAPTER ONE A TRAGEDY IN MEXICO He’d thought he’d been tired the day before in the classroom. Now he was worn out with what he’d done or witnessed. Rodolfo was just a few years old when both his parents were murdered. The house was robbed, with Rodolfo and his father and mother taken away, one by one. There were three armed men, and they were a group of murderers and outlaws. The men who came into the house wanted only money. The house had been left in a caretaker’s hands, but when the men came they quickly took him as well. He knew the man, and he was as simple as they were violent. They took the gold and money their master had hoarded, and then put him to death. The boy went to the kitchen and saw his mother’s corpse. The men were already gone. For a while his mother’s body was kept in the kitchen as they waited for the other captives to return home. Scientific Discourse Communities
This essay discusses the notion of scientific discourse communities. "Scientific Discourse Communities" (SDC) is a way of thinking about the world that is both true and useful. As scientists, we are used to communicating information back and forth to one another in our field of specialty. A "discourse community" of scientists is what this is. Communication patterns are common to all scientific discourse communities, giving them a sense of familiarity and ease. On the other hand, communication patterns that distinguish communities from one another are distinctive. The structure of scientific discourse communities that characterizes scientific discourse communities is analyzed in this essay.

These last words, written by Gerald Murphy in a letter to his wife Gertrude, make up the epigraph of a collection of stories by his brother-in-law, Francis Scott Fitzgerald. When Fitzgerald sent the manuscript to the Murphys to work on in “their house in the beautiful Riviera town of Beaulieu-sur-Mer”, their editorial contributions and changes were recorded at the end of the original.
Gertrude had the manuscript typed into the journal form in which she found it, and Fitzgerald took many of her comments to heart. combined_input: As Neil Armstrong, the first human to land and walk on the Moon during the Apollo 11 mission, what specific scientific tests and experiments did you conduct on the lunar surface with your crewmates Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins? r SerialHOME pipeline pressure Gill HE
generated_output:
AT & A/C A/C COOLANT Temp (F degrees) VACUUM LINE (VL) FITTING NOMINAL DIA. ANSTAL EFFECTIVE RATIO TWO PORTOF OIL VALVE PSI PSI
Neil Armstrong Autobiography, Neal and Harwell Armstrong
CAPCOM Copy From Neil Armstrong, this is Apollo 11, we’re taking a drink, thank you Houston. Neil Armstrong, Apollo 11, this is Houston, you got a drink on Alpha in the crew cabin. Repeat on Alpha in the crew cabin. Oil temperature is normal. We don't read high-pressure ammeters. The low-pressure ammeter just came on, so the pressure will be good. Oil pressure is 54. Now they're starting to build up the propulsion fuel and oxidizer pressure. When they get to the stage where they have all the propulsion systems on, the oil temperature will start to increase. We'll be happy then. When we're talking to you, we would like to talk about the LM. Neil Armstrong, Apollo 11, we’ve got an amber on the EPS system. Neil Armstrong, Apollo 11, Houston, LM EPS amber. Copy on EPS amber. We go through a little drill on the EPS because of its importance during the ascent from the surface as we use it and then the rest of the time we use the power-gimbal as a backup. We went through our EPS drill on startup of the descent prop landing unit. It's all okay. The EPS is still amber but it’s fine. We have just passed orbit insertion. What are our plans for reconfiguring for the descent and the lunar landing? The only thing in the flight plan that we did is we dumped all the propellants because they were really high. We'll be in the transposition sequence now. During the transposition sequence are you going to be working in the command module? Not now. At this point I've got the LM on the Moon.
Neil Armstrong Autobiography, Neal and Harwell
I’ll be outside. We go through a procedure before we start looking out the windows. We’ve got to clean up the EVA suit. All of that has been completed. I'll get out and open the hatch.
What are your visuals at this point? There's a good white spot in the window over to the left. I mean, not the window, but somewhere over there to the left I've got a good, big reflector, maybe 50 feet off our nose. We look up. Yes, I can see the big reflector there. I have seen that now for a few times. About three minutes after we come out I would expect to be able to go out on the surface, and will you be doing the EVA from the command module? I would. It's a matter of time. Now to get that LM down onto the surface is the hard part. It's really a big thing to put down on the surface. I'll work that down onto the surface. Once it’s down there, it becomes a pretty easy transfer from the LM to the surface and then back again and everything will be easy. We can probably do that about three-and-a-half minutes before we go through lunar orbit insertion, so about 30 minutes before landing, it's going to become critical to get this LM down on the Moon. Yes, with everything we've gone through with the burns and the delays and the communication we still are going to be on the schedule we want. We haven't been delayed yet at all. I'll just come off and be outside for a while then we'll go to lunar orbit insertion after we land. As I look at my stopwatch, I can see that the rendezvous should be the rendezvous check time plus 56 minutes for the time I was outside. I think that will work fine, and the LM will still be light since we haven't been using all the fuel. It seems like I've seen that 50-foot reflector just about every time we look up. I must have been looking at it for about the last 30 minutes and it has been coming up that way. It will be at the point where the LM is. But that will have to wait now until we're in lunar orbit. We didn't make it to landing yet. After the landing sequence, how long will it be until the surface of the Moon has cleared your visibility? About thirty minutes. The LM will be
the last in the line of traffic, with the Command Module in the second position of the line and Apollo and the orbiting rendezvous stage will be in its position. When the LM is on the surface, I'll have some time to look around to see where the thing is. How much will you get to look around and where on the Moon will you be able to look as the LM lands? It would be difficult to get too close before landing because of the landing site, but after landing I'll get fairly close to it because it is only about 500 meters away from the point where we actually landed with our descent gear. It is easy to see. I'll be able to get over and around to look at it as we approach the landing site. From the lunar surface it will be difficult to see the orbiting vehicle because it would be so far away. It will be 35 nautical miles out. I think we will be near the landing site when we try to find Tranquility Base. We will be looking to our right from the lunar surface. How much will you be able to see of the lunar horizon from the LM? We are coming in. We can't look around very much until we get down to the point of landing. Once we get the engine started and the landing light on, that allows me to take a quick look around. It is hard to tell where it was and how much detail there was. The big thing is to be able to recognize that we did get a good landing and that the landing gear is down. When the landing sequence begins, how long after do the lunar surface and the Command Module go out of range? Right about the time that we will be descending, I would say, the range between the LM and the Command Module will be about 50 yards, a distance at which we will not be visible to each other. That is the first range, the last range before we start the descent, the point where we are not visible to each other. At that point I will let you know. We started looking back. We must have had that engine going for an awfully long time. We're pretty low. But I was pretty sure I could get back to it. The debate centers on whether orthopedists should use ethylchloride, a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID), and a pain reliever to treat noninflammatory pain caused by a ligament or joint injury. Ethylchloride usually is more effective than an NSAID, and an NSAID helps the anesthetic work. Together, the pain reliever and the local anesthetic form a combination called a multimodal analgesic. But ethylchloride has not undergone human clinical trials, says Joseph A. Bosco, MD, of the Center for Musculoskeletal Care in Dallas and vice president of the American Orthopaedic Association. For now, physicians who use ethylchloride are treating individual patients on an "on a case-by-case basis," says Scott Rodeo, MD, an orthopedist at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York City. Critics: Job creation numbers skewed by part time work SAN FRANCISCO– There have been encouraging signs over the last several months that the nation's unemployment rate is slowly but steadily falling. But a closer look at the data shows a troubling trend: in a sign of weakening job markets, employers are increasingly turning to part time jobs to avoid adding to their payrolls.
The number of part time jobs has grown sharply in the last four months, up 329,000 as of last month's report. Over that same period, full time jobs grew by just 70,000, signaling employers' willingness to take employees only enough to avoid costly full employment benefits and then dial back their payrolls if the demand for work picks up.
That's troubling to those on the bipartisan House Joint Economic Committee, where California Rep. Mike Thompson has served on the Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Subcommittee for the last year. He sees the increased emphasis on part time employees as part of a troubling trend.
"There's no doubt in my mind that the employment numbers are being skewed," said Thompson. "That's not healthy."
Rep. Thompson is particularly dismayed because one of the most important elements to a robust recovery is job growth and the jobs report is, he said, a good indicator.
"That's where all the action is. I don't like using it as an indicator. It's being used by the Federal Reserve and all that," said Thompson. "And I would like to have full employment and a job report to back that up."
While Thompson is right in that the Fed has used the unemployment numbers to show how the economy is improving, economists and some Fed members are also concerned by the jobs growth going only in part time employee positions and not enough full time ones.
Brad Wilson, who teaches economic principles at Cal State Long Beach, said he's heard the same complaints from students and others.
"The only way you get those jobs is if you go part time, because somebody will be willing to work for 185 hours in a month but the employers go back to 2,500 or higher because that way they take away the benefits," said Wilson.
Although there are about 140 million part time employees nationwide, the percentage of job growth in that category relative to full time jobs isn't necessarily abnormal, said Bill Dunkelberg, the chief economist for the National Federation of Independent Business, an association of small businesses nationwide.
"Someone might start a full time job and quit. And a new person might be hired and that person could be part time," said Dunkelberg. "So I don't necessarily think it's a bad thing."
But California Rep. Thompson said that the recent trend isn't something that can be easily explained or that can be written off as something of a non-issue. He said he understands why an employer would hire 200 people for 24 hours each but he said those types of jobs aren't sustainable over the long term and the trend is a growing problem for those who are working in part time positions.
"I've got people who can't find a full-time job," said Thompson in a phone interview. "They're living in their families' basements. We don't know how long these people will be able to do that."
And when these types of jobs no longer exist, Thompson said that there will be many consequences in health, education, retirement and national security for the nation.
"If we're not going to have people who are prepared and have the skills to compete at a global level in the future, then we're in really big trouble," warned Thompson.
In the meantime, the trend of increased part-time employment is unlikely to change anytime soon, according to Dunkelberg.
"The companies feel that the growth is slowing down, and so they're adding to what they already had in part-time employment," said Dunkelberg.
However, he added that overall, the jobs situation is looking good.
"We're well ahead of where we thought we'd be," said Dunkelberg. "The economic trends we thought we'd be experiencing are happening. But the economy we're not in a better situation than it is. So we expectations, it's been a very good thing."

Hackathon on 30 and 31 October 2018 for the project Digital Transparency
Taking on board the input from local government, public and private organisations from the initial workshop, we are running the next phase of this workshop during 2 days of hack time between 30and 31 October 2018. More details here: https://hack.adelaideness.tech/ The Adelaide Hackerspace and the Centre for Advanced Engineering will bring the community together to find innovative solutions that will encourage citizens to share their knowledge of city infrastructure with each other and with local council. We're looking for volunteers, partners and participants. We need some hackers, designers developers for example - but you don't have to do that, if you are a professional - you are welcome on the project as well. Hackathon on Digital Transparency in South Australia

Let me know if you would like to help organise the meeting. Kind Regards, Lukas
Hackathon - Open Access
Open Access is an alternative method of publishing and distributing data that supports academic publications. An increasing number of universities have agreed to use an open access publication when writing academic articles, but not all do, which creates a bottleneck in the current system. We are looking for volunteers who would like to help us with improving this bottleneck by developing a practical Open Access system, which would be able to detect and prevent data from "disappearing" during the process. Involvement should range from writing code to writing documentation and everything in-between. Your contribution can be any time in the week and any number of days in a week. The project dates are flexible and can be determined by the volunteers involved. Please see the details here: https://hack.adelaideness.tech/ The Hackathon will be organized by the AdelaideHackerspace and the Centre for Advanced Engineering. We need some hackers, designers, developers, mentors, partners and participants. Kind Regards, Lukas

Come by and participate -- and we need sponsorship!
Coding In Africa Hackathon
A 48-hour hackathon dedicated to Africa’s tech scene, where developers and designers challenge their creativity to help solve every problem in Africa through technology. Whether it’s healthcare, agriculture, education, community development, and beyond, technology is now more than ever an essential tool that can bridge the gaps in Africa and build better solutions to the challenges it faces. We’re not looking at solutions for Africa, but with Africa! We want African developers to come together to collaboratively innovate and create apps and platforms that address challenges in Africa. We want developers to take their skills to create solutions to problems that they care about. We want developers to create solutions to problems that they would love to see on the continent. We want developers to make the change they want to see. Applications for this event close on May 1st. Don’t leave it too late to apply. The Coding in Africa Hackathon is powered by DevTalks, AppsAfrica.com, and UoN.
Kenyan Innovation Hackathon
You are invited to be part of the Innovation Hackathon that will be organized 27th-29th May 2016 at the School of Continuing Education and Professional Studies Main Campus, Moi University, Kenya. The theme of the hackathon is "Championing Access to Quality Education in Kenya."
Nairobi Hackathon 2016
The First Kenya Hackathon is coming to Kenya! Join us 26-28 May 2016 at the School of Continuing Education and Professional Studies Main Campus, Moi University, Kenya The event is meant to be a catalyst to promote the development of IT solutions designed to solve challenges faced by the university system, specifically in the area of student administration and community engagement. The event is sponsored by 500 Startups, iHub, APM Terminals and TecNakuru and is also underwritten by the Moi University Management as a way of engaging youth in technology as a tool to promote community growth. The event will host over 50 students over weekend in a 2 day design sprint.
Hong Kong Tech-Up Hackathon 2016
On January 29th and 30th, Hong Kong’s top students will join forces with tech pioneers and leaders and hackers for a weekend of technological innovation at the 3rd Annual Hong Kong Tech-Up Hackathon hosted by the Faculty of Business and Economics of The University of Hong Kong in collaboration with BMW, Google, Amazon, Huawei, Intel, The Hong Kong Government's Technology Talent Development Scheme, and The Hong Kong Computer Society. A total of US$ 10,000 in awards is on offer.
